Allow me to tell a little story: As a little boy, I loved singing. One day, a member of the adult choir forgot a tambourine inside the church. I took the set home. The first question my mother asked was how I came to “own” the tambourine. 

When I told the story, she told me to tell her what the sixth commandment says, then she said: “Taking people’s things without their consent is stealing. So what to do right now is run back to the church and put the tambourine back where you picked it.” 

She didn’t punish me, but I learnt a life  lesson. I am no saint but to this day I find myself returning change mistakenly given to me even by the barman. 

 School not just for As 

At the time I spoke with Pastor White, Citam was in the process of investing in the education sector, a venture which has since blossomed from kindergarten to a university. 

He told me the aim was to demonstrate that school shouldn’t just be place to get secular education and score As but also ground for building a wholesome person who has values and ethos besides education. 

He reminded me of my days in high school when the best schools were mostly those learn by the church and missionaries. 

 

*** 

As we celebrate Christmas this week, please let us reflect and plan a return to the old golden values. We can never go wrong in that direction. 



